{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/your-next-hire-should-be-an-applied-data-scientist-977bd5835913", "time": 1683005856.471262, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/your-next-hire-should-be-an-applied-data-scientist-977bd5835913/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Your next hire should be an Applied Data Scientist | by Jeroen van Zeeland | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Your next hire should be an Applied Data Scientist", "description": "Data Scientists are easy to find, finding an all-round data scientist is hard. However, those people will make the difference between failed and successful projects."}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [], "all_paragraphs": ["Data Scientists with a singular skill are easy to find, finding an all-round data scientist is hard. But these 10x resources will make the difference between failed and successful projects.", "A data scientist in a corporate context needs to have a lot of skills on top of the standard list of technical requirements. The hardest part of any data science position is communication and, in the general population, good statistical skills do not necessarily co-occur with social savvy.", "The hardest part of data science is communication.", "When hiring a new data scientist it is important to ask yourself what you are looking for? How do you imagine this person to operate in your business? Are you looking for someone with purely mathematical and statistical skills? Or someone with an affinity for low-level coding? Or, more likely, someone who can be a bridge-builder; someone who can sell the solutions into the business and get buy-in for the projects (and future expenses).", "Most companies are in need of applied data science. Data science specifically applied to solve business challenges. Not for the sake of data science itself, but rather serve a goal. To understand better what applied data science can do for your company we have to understand what the \u201capplied\u201d part actually entails, without all the buzz. This will also help you to identify what your company actually needs, which, perhaps isn\u2019t data science at all.", "The applied data scientist is an interesting role. The applied should be thought of in juxtaposition to a research data scientist. The research data scientist spends his day improving on projects; fiddling around with the most minute details. Researching novel models and finding areas to apply them to.", "The applied data scientist is a trusted business advisor. They communicate with the business, unearth their need and serve that with the tools that apply for the job. Simple data analysis, a data extract, or, when the job calls for it, fancier modelling.", "Don\u2019t get me wrong: there is a place for these research data scientists, but this probably requires a strong support team around them in order to fill the gaps that they are unwilling or unable to fill. These people cannot operate alone in a complex business landscape.", "The applied data scientist combines a wide variety of skills and tools in order to be productive in a business setting.", "So what should you be looking for in a candidate?", "To some extent these roles can be split up, however, each applied data scientist needs to have these crucial skills. These people will tremendously increase the delivery power of the data science team as a whole and they can lift up entire teams.", "So there you go, next time you hire a data scientist, don\u2019t just evaluate their technical prowess but also look for other traits, such as domain knowledge and communication skills. Good luck!", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "CTO for Norway\u2019s largest crime-fighting FinTech and PhD Candidate at the Erasmus University Rotterdam."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F977bd5835913&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav-------